Surgical VOP Assessment Report

Video: 515_simple_interrupted.M4V

Pattern: Simple Interrupted

Rubric Assessment

1. Perpendicular needle passes
Needle presentation was consistently near 90 degrees with mirrored bite depth and width; arcs were followed with controlled regrips and minimal lateral shear.
Score: 3/5 - Competent
2. Gentle tissue handling
Tissue was handled gently with light, intermittent Adson use and minimal crushing; a few extra regrips and strand manipulations added minor, avoidable friction.
Score: 3/5 - Competent
3. Square, secure knots
Instrument ties laid flat and centered; knots appear square and appropriately tightened without strangulation, though throw cadence and tail control could be crisper.
Score: 3/5 - Competent
4. Appropriate approximation/tension
Edges are coapted without blanching or dog-ears; slight variability in tension between stitches but no meaningful gapping where sutures are placed.
Score: 3/5 - Competent
5. Even spacing (0.5-1.0 cm)
Three stitches are placed with roughly uniform intervals within an acceptable range; distribution is limited to the centralâ€“superior portion, leaving the inferior segment under-addressed.
Score: 2/5 - Novice
6. Proper dermal and epidermal apposition
Dermal and epidermal layers are aligned with acceptable apposition; mild eversion where edges were supported, flatter where forceps were omitted but still technically sound.
Score: 3/5 - Competent
7. Economy of time and motion
Movements were purposeful with instruments kept near the field; some time lost to strand organization and regripping, but no excessive departures.
Score: 3/5 - Competent
Average Score: 2.9/5
Summative Assessment:
Final closure shows three simple interrupted sutures on the chosen incision. The work displays disciplined needle control, symmetric bites, and knots centered over the line. Instrument ties are executed methodically with reliable counter-tension, and the edges are brought together without blanching. Overall bimanual coordination is sound and the operative field remains organized. Your limits show in consistency of eversion and distribution. When forceps support is not used, eversion drops; keep a steady, single precise pickup to present the dermis and maintain uniform edge roll. Space the stitches to cover the length you intend to close and maintain the same interval from start to finish. Reduce nonessential regrips and streamline strand handling to tighten the time-motion profile. The result is competent and safe, but I expect more uniform eversion and full-length, evenly distributed coverage.
